The official forecast was only 3%, said Bloomberg.
Contrary to the US, UK and Canadian issuance banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not reduce the basic interest rate, with a reduction in the price of raw materials and falling unemployment leading to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep inflation below 2%, but close to them.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it must discourage inflation so that it doesn't have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation was 3.3 percent of the 15-year-old record, rising from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent in Spain.
Inflation in the euro area has sprung upwards due to rising food and energy prices.
The wheat term prices have increased by 88 percent, and the soya rate has reached its highest value since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and milk products.
The price of oil on the world market this year has risen by 52 percent, and last month it has already cost one barrel of black gold almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will fall from 2.1 percent to 2.5 in 2008, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the level of 12 months of inflation in the next 3-4 months will continue to be around 3 percent, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to double its interest rates in 2008.
