Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increased the risk of the country
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of the Jobbik Magyarszágért movement in August this year, according to the Risk Analysis Division of the Institute of Political Capital, increased the political risk of Hungary and the whole area in several respects.
The company's "attention to risk" writes: in the context of the Hungarian Guard's activities, the greatest political risk is that "violent ethnic tensions between the Roma and the non-Roma people of Hungary may occur in the short term".
The main reason is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is likely to lead to such an action - adds the research institute.
As he writes, all of this can be explained by one of the biggest negligences of Hungarian political leaders: "The public debate on the Roma issue has been left by representatives of public life to representatives of radical and extremist political groups who could build a political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian conflict."
This deepens the problem, makes it impossible for normal dialogue, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts - evaluates the institute.
In addition, the activities of the Hungarian Guard according to the research institute, due to the great attention of domestic and foreign media, "to a large extent the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards faith in the stability of the country and its democratic maturity".
The Institute recalls: part of the reorganization of Hungarian radical and ultra-right groups, which have been getting more and more publicity and vehemence since the autumn of 2006, is that several organizations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007, which are called "national Home Army associations".
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil associations, while they openly proclaim - even armed - the readiness of their members to carry out defensive tasks (in the case of natural disasters, invasion of the country, disruption of order), in addition to pointing out the incompetence of the police, the army, or the state," he adds.
He further notes: all this is happening in a way that seeks to wrap up all sorts of political efforts built on the resistance of society to politics and parties in civilian clothing.
The emphasising of civilization and form of society, therefore, in the case of such groups, is not only a way to avoid legal pitfalls in judicial registration, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a factor in increasing risk from the point of view of neighbouring relations.
"In recent months, Hungary's City has been pointing out as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring states, and the ultranationalist political representatives of some neighbouring countries want to apologize to their own anti-Hungary policy by referring to the formation of Hungarian Guards.
All of this can affect the political stability of the area," he adds.
According to the research institute, the creation of the Hungarian Guard in Central and Eastern Europe is not a unique phenomenon, so that the political risks to the area as a whole have increased.
