After more than 60 years in a confidential regime, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, depicting the 17.5 million victims of Hitler's regime, are opening to the public.
The 47 million archive documents stored in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) were accessible only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and by name, at the request of the former victim or his authorised persons.
Eleven states responsible for the management of archives - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May to open them to scientists and historians.
Given that the process of ratification of this agreement by all states is over, the opening took effect yesterday.
Sensitive information
The free access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow to explore "especially the movements of prisoners, the population of camps and the state of health of forced workers", explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (Comité international de la Croix-route, CICR).
Until recently, several states, among them Germany, were opposed to making these nominal documents available to the public, due to the sensitive nature of some information.
What are supposed to be homosexuality or mental disability of some deportation victims.
Registers of concentration camps or arrest warrants assembled by the Gestapo were collected after the war for practical purposes to find deported or forced work submitted to civilians, to bring them proof of their internation in order to open the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen constitutes only a limited contribution.
"These documents cannot be expected anything substantially new", said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Centre for the Study of Anti-Semitism of Berlin Technische Universität in 2006.
