Congress approved the transposition of MiFID valid from 1 November
In parallel with the parliamentary negotiations that were concluded today by the vote of the Congress on amendments incorporated by the Senate in the bill, the government subject the public hearing of the new law, with a view to both coming into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of individual parties have agreed to negotiate and agree on the best standard for the protection of investors and for the detailed regulation of the activities of the entities needed for the effective functioning of the markets.
The MiFID, which is governed by the Securities Trading Act, foresees the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between the different supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will enable financial consultancy services to be provided to both specialised companies, natural or legal persons, and create a new type of financial services companies (ESIS), financial consultancy companies (AFIs), which join securities companies, securities brokerage agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the execution of operations with financial instruments is expanding by connecting to regulated secondary markets multilateral trading systems and orders internalisation systems that will compete with current stockbrokers.
Furthermore, the law obliges investment service companies to disseminate information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and ways of dealing with the risk, and requires that all operations carried out to simplify surveillance by the CNMV be reported.
During the negotiations in the Congress Trade Commission, several adjustments were included, among which the outstanding ones, for securitised receivables to be considered as a "complex" financial instrument due to the high risk to the investor, which was demonstrated by what occurred in the US with high risk mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally set out the functions that can be held by bachelors in the field of economics and business management for 30 years after the royal decree was approved in 1977, which sets out the professional functions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate has included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary that will work abroad, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide services for product trading and customer acquisition for different investment firms at the same time.
